    c5=6, c7=0, nc=12, alpha2=0

  H=29 tournament (bits=739):
    Out-degrees: [3, 3, 0, 2, 4, 4, 5]
    c5=6, c7=0, nc=12, alpha2=1

  Delta: nc(29)-nc(25) = 0, alpha2(29)-alpha2(25) = 1
  Check: 2*delta_nc + 4*delta_a2 = 4
  Actual delta H = 4 = 4

  c5: t25=6, t29=6
  c7: t25=0, t29=0
  c3: t25=6, t29=6
  => c3 and c5 are SAME. Difference must be in c7!
     c7 difference = 0
     This gives alpha_1 difference = 0
     2*delta_alpha1 = 0 = delta H? YES

======================================================================
ANALYSIS 3: SYSTEMATIC Ś WHAT DISTINGUISHES ALL AMBIGUOUS CASES?
======================================================================

  Score (0, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5):
    lambda=... (21 values), H=[25, 29]
    c5=[6], c7=[0]
      (c5=6, c7=0) -> H = [25, 29] [STILL AMBIGUOUS]
    => (c5, c7) does NOT resolve! Deeper invariant needed.

  Score (1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 5):
    lambda=... (21 values), H=[27, 29]
    c5=[4, 5], c7=[1]
      (c5=4, c7=1) -> H = 29
      (c5=5, c7=1) -> H = 27
    => (c5, c7) RESOLVES the ambiguity!

  Score (1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4, 6):
